I was >>30677969
Gather 'round, potential writers. Right now I'm going through an editing phase, so this is exactly what I'm working on.
I'll paraphrase what I said the previous thread. The quoted example from D15C0RD is like one of my first drafts: almost all dialogue. Some writers start with that, others do the exposition, yet others the narrative.
And there's nothing wrong with a few paragraphs that that are all one mode. It leaves things on the table, but if that's the writer's intent then so be it.

A lack of action or attributive tags allows an exchange to read as faster paced. The conventional wisdom is to break that up every so often to avoid talking heads.
I tend to read dialogue from law enforcement with a crisper diction. As the MC isn't much of a threat I see this like a lawyer leading the witness during testimony. Any small action tags interspersing the dialogue should reflect that. Maybe she's writing in a notebook or gesturing with her pen.

If I wanted a slower pace during the dialogue, I'd add some background action or events. Officer is quick to respond, MC takes time to wrap his head around it.
On the other hand, if we want a tighter shot in cinematographic terms then some narration fits the bill.

Pacing a scene takes revision. After going back and reading the couple thousand words you binned, the original commenter was far too harsh.
You've got some narration and exposition, I never got lost with who was speaking.
Maybe our MC is so shaken up or shock that he isn't noticing at this point. Not a single detail on how Judy holds herself. You told us Judy was embarrassed, her speech reflected it, but you didn't show us.

I'll repeat in short something I've said before. Writing in someone else's world, in this case Zootopia, doesn't absolve you of the responsibility of painting the picture for the reader. I've never seen the movie and don't care to. If you show (as in show, don't tell) us Judy, I'll feel the scene.

They knew they weren't and, rightly so, only cared about their family and/or themselves. Dehumanizing each other is how they survived, how they kept themselves and their family safe, and it was like that since time memorial for us that it became as easy as breathing. Columbus cared only for wealth, and these "savages" were merely tools. They did not share his culture so it meant nothing to him. Same with hitler, and same with stalin (less culture and more political opponents and "useless" people)
